","1200":"1200","1222":"1222","1243":"1243","1287":"1287","Kingston Lisle, Berkshire, England":"Kingston Lisle, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","Chesterton, Cambridgeshire, England":"Chesterton, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Harewood, Yorkshire, England":"Harewood, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"FitzGerald","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, Liam, Aidan, Bridgid, Caitlin, Donal, Fitz, Fitzgerald, Ciaran, Colum, Dermot.","Irish: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name <i>Gerald</i> (see   Gerald  ), ‘son of <i>Gerald</i>’. This is a very common Anglo-Norman name in Ireland, where it has been Gaelicized as <b>Mac Gearailt</b>. Irish bearers of the name claim descent from <i>Gerald</i> Fitzwalter de Windsor, constable of Pembroke Castle in the early 12th century, whose grandson Raymond (or Redmond) ‘le Gros’ <i>FitzGerald</i> (died after 1185) led the invasion of Ireland on behalf of Strongbow in 1170. A branch of the family held the title Knight of Glin from at least 1299–2011."],"variants":[{"name":"Jarrell","meanings":["Irish: altered form of   Fitzgerald  .","English (Kent and Middlesex; of Norman origin): variant of <b>Jarrold</b>, itself a variant of   Gerald  ."]},{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice FitzGerald was born in 1224, in Kingston Lisle, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Henry FitzGerrold, was 50 and her mother, Ermentrude Talbot, was 24. She married Robert Lisle in 1262, in Harewood, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1270, in her hometown, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1224–1270":"1224–1270","1215–1284":"1215–1284","1222–Male":"1222–Surnud","1257–1260":"1257–1260","–Male":"Surnud","1243–1284":"1243–1284","1246–1284":"1246–1284","1248–1287":"1248–1287","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1200–1242":"1200–1242","1242":"1242","1175":"1175","1262":"1262","1284":"1284","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1248":"1248","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1257":"1257","1200":"1200","1222":"1222","1243":"1243","1287":"1287","Kingston Lisle, Berkshire, England":"Kingston Lisle, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chesterton, Cambridgeshire, England":"Chesterton, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Harewood, Yorkshire, England":"Harewood, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1224–1270":"1224–1270","1215–1284":"1215–1284","1222–Male":"12